## Why

The pre-commit validation scheduler was cancelling healthy parallel checks after a process-session leader exited before one of its supervised helpers closed inherited output descriptors. That made the shift-left gate unreliable.

## How

- extend the bounded post-exit output-drain allowance from two to five seconds;
- retain process ownership, cancellation, output limits, and all validation budgets;
- add a Unix regression test for a short-lived owned descendant that closes inherited output after the leader exits;
- verify focused process tests, the complete pre-commit gate, and the complete pre-push gate.

Closes #534

## Superseded / not planned

This proposal conflicts with the canonical RustTable execution contract in #158 and the implemented queue/PR governance from #446:

- one coherent implementation issue maps to one ready-for-review squash PR;
- source ownership, dependencies, body hashes, acceptance evidence, and corrective successors remain issue-specific;
- a PR cannot close two independent source-map contracts merely because their implementations are adjacent;
- multiple isolated workers may collaborate on one issue/PR without changing issue-to-PR cardinality.

Requiring exactly two issues per PR would weaken source-to-Rust traceability, complicate optimistic body-hash/readiness enforcement, and make partial completion or rollback ambiguous. It is therefore not adopted.

No standalone documentation PR should target this issue. Future agent-workflow wording must remain consistent with #158, #446, #518, #555, and the repository’s current PR contract.

